   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="essay">
            <head>
               <bibl>
                  <author type="writer">
                     <name>
                        <ref target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Elizabeth Inchbald</ref>
                     </name>
                  </author>
                  <title type="main" level="a">REMARKS [on <hi rendition="#italics"><title>The
                           Grecian Daughter</title></hi>].<note>"Remarks." <hi rendition="#italics"
                                 ><title><title>The Grecian Daughter</title>; A Tragedy, In Five
                              Acts; As Performed at the Theatre Royal, <ref
                                 target="people.html#CoventGarden">Covent Garden</ref>. By <ref
                                 target="people.html#MurphyArthur">Arthur Murphy</ref>, Esq. Printed
                              Under the Authority of the Managers From the Prompt Book. With Remarks
                              by <ref target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Mrs.
                           Inchbald</ref></title></hi>. London: Printed for Longman, Hurst, Rees,
                        and Orme, Paternoster Row, pp. 3-5. <hi rendition="#italics"><title
                              level="m">The British Theatre; or, A Collection of Plays, Which Are
                              Acted At the Theatres Royal, <ref target="people.html#DruryLane">Drury
                                 Lane</ref>, <ref target="people.html#CoventGarden">Covent
                                 Garden</ref>, and <ref target="people.html#Haymarket"
                                 >Haymarket</ref>. Printed Under the Authority of the Managers from
                              the Prompt Books. With Biographical and Critical Remarks, by <ref
                                 target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Mrs. Inchbald.</ref></title></hi>
                        In Twenty-Five Volumes. Vol. XV. <hi rendition="#italics">
                           <title><ref target="people.html#BarbarossaAruj"
                           >Barbarossa</ref></title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"><title>Way to
                              Keep Him</title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"><title>All in the
                              Wrong</title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"><title>Grecian
                              Daughter</title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"><title>Know Your Own
                              Mind</title></hi>. London: Printed for Longman, Hurst, Rees, and Orme,
                        Paternoster Row. 1808. The first performance of this play was staged at the
                           <ref target="people.html#DruryLane">Theatre Royal, Drury Lane</ref> on
                        February 26<hi rendition="#sup">th</hi>, 1772. Laura DeWitt and Mary A.
                        Waters edited this essay for <hi rendition="#italics">The Criticism
                           Archive</hi>.</note>
                     <lb rendition="#center"/>______ </title>
               </bibl>
            </head>
            <p>This tragedy has been so rapturously applauded on the stage, and so severely
               criticised in the closet,<note>Closet drama refers to plays read privately rather
                  than watched as a performance.</note> that it is a task of peculiar difficulty to
               speak either of its beauties or its defects, with any degree of certainty. To
               conciliate both the auditor and the reader, both the favourable and the unfavourable
               critic, the "<title>Grecian Daughter</title>" demands a set of Remarks for each side
               of the question&#8212;and the good-natured side shall have precedence.</p>

            <p>This play had, on its first appearance, the most brilliant success, and still holds a
               place in the list of dramas performed during every season.<note><hi
                     rendition="#italics"><title>The Grecian Daughter</title></hi> was an instant
                  critical and commercial success, and it remained popular through the end of the
                     18<hi rendition="#sup">th</hi> century.</note> There is a splendour of
               decoration, a glow of martial action, events of such deep interest, and, above all, a
               moral of such excellent tendency which concludes the performance, that its attraction
               can readily be accounted for, without the slightest imputation upon the judgment of
               the public.</p>

            <p>Perhaps, of all the events recorded in history, that filial piety, on which the fable
               of this play is founded, may be classed amongst the most affecting&#8212;yet it was
               one the most hazardous for a dramatist to adopt; for nothing less than complete skill
               could have given to this singular occurrence effectual force, joined to becoming
               delicacy. In this arduous effort <ref target="people.html#MurphyArthur">Mr.
                  Murphy</ref> has evinced the most exact judgment, and the nicest execution.</p>
            <fw type="sig"><hi rendition="#smcaps">b 2</hi></fw>
            <pb n="4"/>
            <p>If this tragedy has not the smooth flowing verse of <ref
                  target="people.html#OtwayThomas">Otway</ref>, <ref
                  target="people.html#ThomsonJames">Thomson</ref>, or <ref
                  target="people.html#RoweNicholas">Rowe</ref>, it possesses, in energy and fire,
               charms more theatrical; nor does the heroic so wholly engross every scene, but that
               it yields, at times, to melting pathos.</p>

            <p>Another praise due to this production is, that wonderful events take place by the
               most natural agency. Incidents arise progressively from each other, till the last,
               and greatest incident of all, fills every mind with enthusiasm in the cause of virtue
               and justice&#8212;in the joy of an empire made free by the overthrow of its
                  tyrant.<note>The action of the play centers around Euphrasia and her father,
                  Evander, the King of Syracuse who has been deposed and imprisoned by the tyrant
                  usurper Dionysius. Euphrasia manages to free her father, and when Dionysius
                  finally finds them hiding in a temple and comes to kill them, Euphrasia instead
                  kills Dionysius with her dagger.</note></p>
            <lb/>
            <p>It is hardly possible to read this tragedy of the "<title>Grecian Daughter</title>,"
               without laughing as well as crying. Some passages excite tears, whilst certain
               high-sounding sentences, with meaning insignificant, are irresistibly risible.</p>

            <p>The popular story, from which the fable of this tragedy is produced,<note><hi
                     rendition="#italics"><title>The Grecian Daughter</title></hi> is based off the
                  story of Cimon and Pero, also called "<title>Roman Charity</title>," as recorded
                  in <ref target="people.html#MaximusValerius">Valerius Maximus</ref>' <hi
                     rendition="#italics"><title>Factorum ac Dictorum Memorabilium Libri
                     IX</title></hi> (<hi rendition="#italics"><title>Nine Books of Memorable Deeds
                        and Sayings</title></hi>, c. 27-31 C.E.).</note> and the surprising event in
               the last scene&#8212;where a woman performs that, which a whole army has in vain
               attempted&#8212;together with the powerful acting of <ref
                  target="people.html#BarryAnn">Mrs. Barry</ref> in the part of Euphrasia, rendered
               the play greatly attractive when it was first performed; and as those causes of
               attraction still remain, or rather, an improvement is introduced by <ref
                  target="people.html#SiddonsSarah">Mrs. Siddons</ref>'s appearance in the heroine,
               the work is still of use of the theatre.<note>The role of Euphrasia became a crucial
                  stepping stone to fame for many actresses of the late 18<hi rendition="#sup"
                     >th</hi> century. <ref target="people.html#BarryAnn">Ann Street Barry</ref>
                  debuted the role, and <ref target="people.html#SiddonsSarah">Sarah Siddons</ref>'
                  performance of Euphrasia became an audience favorite beginning in 1782.</note></p>

            <p>The men's characters have been all sacrificed by the author to the valour of the
               woman&#8212;he has made his female do the deed of a man, and his best man perform the
               act of a child.<note>When Euphrasia visits her imprisoned father, she suckles him
                  from her own breast to prevent his starvation.</note></p>
            <pb n="5"/>
            <p>Though Evander ranks as the first male character in this play, no actor likes to
               appear in the part. He would rather be inferior, and less infirm.</p>

            <p>As <ref target="people.html#MurphyArthur">Mr. Murphy</ref> had much theatrical
               experience as well as taste, it is astonishing that the personage most talked of,
               most praised, and by far the most perfect character in the whole drama, should never
               make his appearance!</p>

            <p>Timoleon is a great warrior and a good man;<note>Timoleon is the famous warrior who
                  leads the Greek armies to liberate Syracuse from Dionysius. Although he is
                  mentioned frequently, he does not appear in the play.</note> and it seems
               wonderful how the audience, on the first night of the play, would quit the theatre
               without seeing him. Yet it was but modesty and respect in the author, not to bring so
               magnanimous a hero on the scene, to speak bad poetry.</p>

            <p>The great tragic dramatist, <ref target="people.html#OtwayThomas">Otway</ref>, wrote
               miserable comedies: Let it be no disgrace to <ref target="people.html#MurphyArthur"
                  >Murphy</ref> that he has written an indifferent tragedy. By the merit of his
               comic scenes, his tragic ones are perhaps judged, and in the comparison lose half
               their value.</p>
            <fw type="sig"><hi rendition="#smcaps">b 3</hi></fw>
         </div>
      </body>
